Theory of Strings in Java
What is a String?
In Java, a String is a sequence of characters.
Example: "Hello", "Java", "Saniya" are all strings.
Java provides a special class called String in the java.lang package to handle text data.
Declaring a String
You can create a string in two ways:
1. Using String literal:
String name = "Saniya";
2. Using new keyword:
String name = new String("Saniya");
Both create a string, but literals are stored in the String Constant Pool, while the new keyword stores them in heap memory.
Common String Methods
Method	Description	Example	Output
length()	Returns length of string	"Java".length()	4
charAt(index)	Returns character at given position	"Java".charAt(2)	'v'
toLowerCase()	Converts to lowercase	"HELLO".toLowerCase()	"hello"
toUpperCase()	Converts to uppercase	"java".toUpperCase()	"JAVA"
equals(str)	Compares two strings (case-sensitive)	"Java".equals("java")	false
equalsIgnoreCase(str)	Compares ignoring case	"Java".equalsIgnoreCase("java")	true
concat(str)	Joins two strings	"Hello".concat("World")	"HelloWorld"
substring(start, end)	Extracts part of string	"Saniya".substring(0,3)	"San"
replace(old, new)	Replaces character or word	"apple".replace('p','b')	"abble"
trim()	Removes spaces from start and end	" Java ".trim()	"Java"
String is Immutable
In Java, Strings are immutable, meaning once created, they cannot be changed.
If you modify a string, a new object is created in memory.
Example:
String s = "Hello";
s.concat(" World");
System.out.println(s);  // Output: Hello
If you print s, it stays the same. To save the new value, you must assign it:
s = s.concat(" World");  // Now s = "Hello World"
Mutable Strings
If you want to modify strings frequently, use:
StringBuilder (faster, not thread-safe)
StringBuffer (slower, thread-safe)
Example:
StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder("Hello");
sb.append(" Java");
System.out.println(sb);  // Output: Hello Java
Summary:
String = sequence of characters.
Immutable (cannot be changed).
Common operations: compare, join, substring, replace.
For editable strings, use StringBuilder or StringBuffer.
